[normal]Q291[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I welcome you to this meeting of the Scottish Affai
[normal]rs Committee. This is our third evidence session 
[normal]in our 
[normal]inquiry 
[normal]into land reform in 
[normal]Scotland
[normal]. It would be helpful if for the record you said who you were, what your background was and what your area of expertise was. Is this the first time we have had two professors out of two? No. We have had scor
[normal]es of professors before, but we 
[normal]have
[normal] usually
[normal] always had a normal 
[normal]mortal with them 
[normal]rather than
[normal] exclusively professors.
[normal]              
[normal]Graeme Morrice:[bold] We 
[normal]had three
[normal] at one time
[normal].
[normal]Chair:[bold] Okay. Tell us who you are
[normal], then
[normal].
[normal]Professor Cheshire[bold]: 
[normal]My name is Paul Cheshire. I am professor of economic geography at the LSE. I am interested i
[normal]n urban economics, land markets and
[normal] land use planning effects viewed from an economic perspective.
[normal]Professor Adams[bold]: I am David Adams. I am the professor of property and urban studies at the 
[normal]University
[normal] of 
[normal]Glasgow
[normal]. My interest is in the interaction between planning and property real estate markets, primarily in an urban context. In relation to this inquiry, I am one of the advisers to the Scottish Government’s land reform review group.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q292[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Thank you very much. 
[normal]As you will appreciate, most of 
[normal]us here do not have a backgrou
[normal]nd in this area of work. Don’t
[normal] feel you will be insulting us by telling 
[normal]us very
[normal] 
[normal]basic things. W
[normal]e would much rather be told very basic things twice than have them skimmed over. 
[normal]Given the fact that l
[normal]and reform in Scotland has traditionally focused on rural
[normal] rather than urban land—w
[normal]e 
[normal]are interested in both of those—
[normal]and the distortions caused by the tax system
[normal], d
[normal]oes it make sense for us to make, however, a substantial differentiation between the 
[normal]way in which urban
[normal] land markets
[normal] 
[normal]and rural land markets work, or is there a substantial degree of overlap?
[normal]Professor Adams[bold]: T
[normal]here is a substantial degree of overlap
[normal] if 
[normal]you look at markets in a particular
[normal] way
[normal],
[normal] which places great emphasis on th
[normal]e behaviour and
[normal] strategies of the owner
[normal]. I
[normal]t looks at the relationship between the strategies and key players, such as estate agents, so there are ways in which you look at land markets that can be as applicable in urban and rural areas.
[normal]              
[normal]Having said that, the issues are rather 
[normal]different. In urban areas, certainly in key settlements in 
[normal]Scotland
[normal] such as 
[normal]Glasgow
[normal], there is a huge overhang of land 
[normal]that is not being used. It has been 
[normal]vacant and derelict for a long period of time. In rural areas
[normal], such
[normal] la
[normal]nd is very rare in terms of 
[normal]unused land on the Scottish Government’s vacant and derelict land register, for example, and the issues are much more about ownership structures and the extent to which
[normal],
[normal] as a result of those ownership structures
[normal],
[normal] the land is being used to 
[normal]sustainable effect or not.
[normal]Professor Cheshire[bold]: I would come at it from a rather different view. My basic message to you would b
[normal]e that all the work
[normal] that
[normal] I
[normal] 
[normal]have done, 
[normal]and
[normal] that
[normal] an in
[normal]creasing number of scholars
[normal] around the world have done
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]reinforces the conclusion that 
[normal]land markets are 
[normal]amazingly efficient at capitalising almost everything. By “capitalising
[normal],”
[normal] I mean that the price of land reflec
[normal]ts everything about its value and
[normal] use, including intangible things like not just cur
[normal]rent aircraft noise 
[normal]but expected future aircraft noise. Some very interesting work is g
[normal]oing on in 
[normal]Berlin
[normal] at the moment. T
[normal]here is a 
[normal]proposal for a 
[normal]new airport
[normal],
[normal] and the proposed flight paths and opening date have been changed over time. Each of those changes is already capitalised into the land markets in 
[normal]Berlin
[normal]. I
[normal]f you try to help poor farmers by giving them subsidies, it gets capitalised i
[normal]nto the price of land. I
[normal]f you give
[normal] inheritance tax relief
[normal]s
[normal] to farmers to try to keep family farms going, it gets capitalised into the price of land and squeezes 
[normal]family farmers out. I
[normal]f you give subsidies to farmers, it gets capitalis
[normal]ed in the price of rural land. I
[normal]f you give planning permission with parti
[normal]cular obligations, t
[normal]he expected value of those obligations
[normal]—because it is always in the future—is 
[normal]again reflected in the price of land. This seems remarkably efficient
[normal],
[normal] given
[normal] that
[normal] 
[normal]we know there is
[normal] a fair degree of
[normal] 
[normal]apparent monopoly in land markets
[normal], but you still have trade
[normal] and it is trade on the margin that really matters. In urban areas
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]because 
[normal]lots of houses are changing hands
[normal],
[normal] the process
[normal] may be rather quicker and 
[normal]complete than it is in rural areas where the volume of trades is rather less relative to the total stock of land.
[normal]&#xa0;
