[normal]have the same distortion
[normal]?
[normal]Professor Cheshire[bold]: Here I disagree with my colleague. It seems to me that the enormous distortions in the urban market arise from the planning system and the separation of use categories. You are allocating supply for different uses independently of market prices and generating distortions at quite incredible levels. For example, agricultural land to the north of 
[normal]Oxford
[normal] is worth about £10,000 a hectare. If you can get permission to build houses on it, it is worth about £8
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million a hectare.
[normal]Professor Adams[bold]: That
[normal] point in relation to the difference between agricultural and urban land is entirely correct. I have slightly different figures, but the point is correct. Within the kinds of urban areas I am talking about, which are the industrial areas of Scotland that have undergone huge structural change, it is not very hard to persuade the planners to give you permission for whatever you want to do. In those areas—we are
[normal] a million miles from the south-
[normal]east of England—the huge constraint is not planning. They will welcome you with open arms. There has been criticism of the way 
[normal]Glasgow
[normal] has regenerated over a period of 20 or 30 years. The arms have been too open there. There is not a lot of evidence in those areas that the constraint is primarily a planning one.
[normal]Professor Cheshire[bold]: I have done research on this. You can look at a paper in 
[normal]T
[normal]he
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Economic Journal
[normal] in 2008
[normal],
[normal] where we estimated the regulatory cost in about 20 office centres across Europe. While 
[normal]Glasgow
[normal] was lower than, say, 
[normal]Birmingham
[normal], which is fairly shocking, it still stood out. All British office centres, with the single exception of 
[normal]Newcastle
[normal], had very substantial regulatory costs associated with their restrictiveness. Like Glasgow—this is from the top of my head
[normal], from memory
[normal]—it was equivalent to about a 200% tax on the costs of construction associated with the supply restriction.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q370[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Professor Adams, you are about to disagree.
